Pag. 9. Nay further (saith W. Davis) this would destroy the very being of God, according to the saying of the Rhodian Poet, Quisquis ubi
que habitat maxime nusquam habitat, i. e. He that every where can be, in no place never found is he. For if God be every where alike, then either every thing is God, 〈◊〉 then every thing must be worshipped, or else nothing is God. If we grant the first, that promotes Idolatry in the highest degree of it; if the second, it introduces Atheism in the utmost extream of it;
what a mad piece of absurd and jumbled Divinity would this be? but that God is every where present by his sacred Attributes, is in no wise denyed by us, quoting Psal. 139.7, 8, 10. and 147.5.
